    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-12-05T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-12-05T07:00:00-05:00" n="782"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d782">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">320/12–551: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The United States Representative at the United Nations</hi>
                        (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Austin</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">
                            <gloss target="#t_niact1">niact</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-12-05T13:00:00+01:00"
                            >December 5, 1951—1 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Delga1">Delga</gloss> 511. Subject: Korea.</p>
                <p>Heavy pressures from UK, Fr, Aust and Can to hold informal discussions concerning
                    post-armistice moves Korea are building up as news from Korea gives rise to
                    feeling armistice might soon be concluded.</p>
                <p>Pearson (Canada) is leaving Paris for Ottawa Thurs a. m. and has requested Gross
                    to meet 6 p. m. this evening Paris time.</p>
                <p>In accordance with <gloss target="#t_Gadel1">Gadel</gloss> 327 [<hi rend="italic"
                        >323</hi>], December 2,<note n="1" xml:id="d782fn1">See footnote 3, <ref
                            target="#pg_1211">p. 1211</ref>.</note> we have rejected requests for
                    conversations subject matter <gloss target="#t_Delga1">Delga</gloss> 464 and
                        465.<note n="2" xml:id="d782fn2">Both dated December 1, <ref
                            target="#pg_1028">pp. 1208</ref> and <ref target="#pg_1210"
                        >1210</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>In view of Pearson’s imminent departure and his repeated request for informal
                    exchange of views, we have found it difficult without extreme embarrassment to
                    refuse his request. In view of explicit instruction <gloss target="#t_Gadel1"
                        >Gadel</gloss> 327 [<hi rend="italic">323</hi>], urgently request Dept to
                    authorize by Niact message purely exploratory discussion with Pearson primary
                    object of which would be to ascertain his views. We would, of course, make it
                    completely clear that US position still under consideration.<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d782fn3">
                        <p>Telegram <gloss target="#t_Gadel1">Gadel</gloss> 343, December 5, to
                            Paris, responded as follows:</p>
                        <p>“No objection, <gloss target="#t_Delga1">Delga</gloss> 511. Dept’s
                            further comments Korea will fol. Since we are reviewing whole situation
                            here with <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss>, you shld carefully avoid
                            any commitments re our position.” (320/12–551)</p>
                    </note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Austin</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
